author: @amdreallyfast
text: I took this tutorial and ran with it, combining other of your tutorials on generators and multiprocessing with a stackoverflow post on built-in python functionality for generating all subsets of a set to create a multiprocessing, brute-force, all-combination feature set KMeans classifier just for kicks to try to see which combination of feature sets would yield the highest accuracy (taking into account the reciprocal of the accuracy if <50%).   I haven't run the whole thing yet because 13 features (14 sans "survived" = 13) yields 2^13 = 8192 combinations. Ran 700 of them though and found, shockingly, that the presence of "boat" appeared to have a significant impact on survival rate. Not as shockingly though, using only the feature set "boat" yielded ~81% accuracy, and so did (boat, sex), (boat, parch), and (boat, sex, parch).  I don't know what to make of this. Is it saying that other features were pretty much useless if they got into a lifeboat? Note that I replaced nan with 0. Hopefully that didn't mess it up.
